, Suffolk, England":"Nayland, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pitchels","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Pitcher  ; a post-medieval modification of the surname, with excrescent  <i>-s</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Pitcher","meanings":["English (mainly eastern and southern): from an agent derivative of Middle English <i>pich</i> ‘pitch’, hence an occupational name for a caulker, one who sealed the seams of ships or barrels with pitch.","Possibly from German <i>Pitscher</i>, from a short form of a personal name formed with Old High German <i>bītan</i> ‘to endure’, or <i>bittan</i> ‘to wish or ask for’, or from a variant of   Pietsch  ."]},{"name":"Pitches","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Pitchers  ."]}]},{"name":"Rebecca","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, from the Latin form of the Hebrew name <i>Rebekah</i>, borne by the wife of Isaac, who was the mother of Esau and Jacob (Genesis 24–27). The Hebrew root occurs in the Bible only in the vocabulary word <i>marbek</i> ‘cattle stall’, and its connection with the name is doubtful. In any case, Rebecca was Aramean, and the name probably has a source in Aramaic. It has always been common as a Jewish name; in England and elsewhere it began to be used also by Christians from the 14th century onwards and especially at the time of the Reformation, when Old Testament names became popular. It was very common among the Puritans in the 17th century, and has enjoyed a tremendous vogue in England since the latter part of the 20th century, among people of many different creeds. In Scotland this is found as an Anglicized form of Beathag ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Rebecca Pitchels was born about 1501, in Nayland, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Jo